</comment>

        <comment>
  <id>102431247</id>
  <body><![CDATA[<i>Matt wrote: "I think before we judge O'Connor too harshly for her characterization of the book, it's important to look at a few things. (To preface: I really love TKaM, but I partially agree with O'Connor.) Why..."</i><br /><br />Matt, I don't think anyone has judged O'Connor harshly for her statement that TKAM is a children's book. You made some apt statements in your comment. However, I cannot agree with your statement "how sickly sweet and unbelievable Atticus' morality is, and how he's more of a fable or a 'hero for kids to emulate' than a real person."<br /><br />The fact of the matter is that I've known any number of "Atticus Finches" in my life. Circuit Judge Henry Holman Mize of Tuscaloosa County was an Alabama Legislator who was considered a likely candidate for Governor. He sponsored legislation to make it unlawful to wear a mask in a public assembly. In essence, in the early 1950s, Judge Mize unmasked the Ku Klux Klan in Alabama. After the impact of his legislation sank in, he received death threats at his family home. He never served another term in the legislature. And, of course, he never became Governor. His motivation for sponsoring the legislature was a raid by members of the Klan on a girl scout camp out in which both black and white children participated. The children were terrified.<br /><br />The Southern Law and Poverty Center bankrupted the Klan following the lynching of Michael Donald in Mobile, Alabama, in 1981. The Center was founded in 1971 by a white Jew named Morris Dees. Since its founding, Dees and his dedicated staff of young black and white attorneys established Klan Watch and now maintains a hate crimes watch.<br /><br />It is easy to reflect on earlier times and dismiss the efforts of individuals for being just a good person. However, change had to begin somewhere. And it began with individuals who recognized that "all men are created equal," and worked side by side with black Americans to see that they achieved that status as granted by our supposed Declaration of Independence.<br /><br />I also do not see Atticus Finch treating the black citizens of Maycomb County with condescension, but individuals entitled to equal protection under the law.<br /><br />Did Atticus not believe in what he sought defending Tom Robinson? I don't think so. I remember his imploring the jury, "For God's Sake do your duty!"<br /><br />Not to demean your comments, I must ask you if you lived through the Civil Rights Movement? I have seen the ridiculously unmasked Klan demonstrating outside a popular cafeteria to deter black citizens from eating there. I have been called a Nigger Lover for having black friends in highschool. And I must say many whites suffered the wrath of the Klan during the summer of the Freedom Riders and King's march from Selma to Montgomery.<br /><br />In closing I must say your comments concerning this novel are much in conflict with your five star rating if you find it a mere fable.<br /><br />In short it is much easier to talk the talk than walk the walk. You must know what times were like, you must know the price that was paid by so many individuals to bring about any form of equality in this country. <br /><br />No, I am not so naive to believe there no longer exists racism in this country. I believe it exists in every state of the Union and it exists in countries throughout the world sometimes simply on the basis of clan affiliation or religious belief.<br /><br />However, it is literature such as To Kill a Mockingbird and many other works from different lands that still offers hope for a better world. Such works are only fables when considered with cynicism.<br /><br />You are entitled to speak every word which you have written in your comment. However, perhaps your comments would be better made in a review written by you rather than mine.]]></body>
  
